Not really, because what we want is to figure out what the chance is
that any given L is purple.

We already know one truth from castle.des that can be gleaned from
direct observation:  there will be some L's at the castle.  27 random
monsters are generated, spread evenly across 10 swap slots and 10 types
of monsters; this means that 3 slots are only used twice.

What this means is that there is a 70% chance of the castle having three L,
and a 30% chance of the castle having two L.  From that, once we know the
chance that any given L will be generated purple, we can extrapolate that
over the 70%-chance-of-three and 30%-chance-of-two to determine what the
actual chance is of seeing a purple L at the castle.

In this case, we saw 56 liches, 7 of which were purple, giving a (very
inaccurate) 1/8 chance of any given L being purple.  If there are three
liches that's a 33%-ish chance of one being purple; if there are two that's
a 25%-ish chance; works out to about 30% or so overall.

We both agree that the sample size is far too small, of course, so the
above paragraph serves as nothing more than handwaving until I get a
chance to look and see what the _real_ chances are per level.  But this
is why I summarised it the way I did.  :)

